00:00:29.136 --> 00:00:31.404
for that 1st pound of fruit,

00:00:31.404 --> 00:00:32.270
so we spend it there.

00:00:32.270 --> 00:00:35.250
Then for the 3rd pound or
for the 3rd bar of chocolate.

00:00:35.250 --> 00:00:39.604
Then it became equal to spend
for the 1st pound of fruit

00:00:39.604 --> 00:00:42.804
so then we spent the next $2
on that 1st pound of fruit

00:00:42.804 --> 00:00:44.751
because the price of fruit were $2.

00:00:44.751 --> 00:00:46.079
What I want to do in this video

00:00:46.079 --> 00:00:48.605
is explore what happens
when I change the price

00:00:48.605 --> 00:00:50.001
of the chocolate bars.

00:00:50.001 --> 00:00:54.465
What happens to our marginal
utility per dollar over here?

00:00:54.465 --> 00:00:57.603
In particular, what happens
to the quantity demanded?

00:00:57.603 --> 00:00:59.836
If you think about what we're doing it,

00:00:59.836 --> 00:01:01.748
we figured out with 1 price

00:01:01.748 --> 00:01:03.208
what was the quantity demanded,

00:01:03.208 --> 00:01:04.534
we demanded 3 bars.

00:01:04.534 --> 00:01:05.866
If we change the price

00:01:05.866 --> 00:01:07.203
and we get another quantity demanded,

00:01:07.203 --> 00:01:10.209
we're essentially starting
to plot our our demand curve

00:01:10.209 --> 00:01:12.273
and we can actually
derive our demand curve

00:01:12.273 --> 00:01:15.081
from this information right over here.

00:01:15.081 --> 00:01:16.580
Let's see how we could do that.

00:01:16.580 --> 00:01:23.420
Let's now assume that our
chocolate bars are $2.

00:01:23.420 --> 00:01:25.069
Now we're going to calculate.

00:01:25.069 --> 00:01:27.669
The marginal utility per dollar,

00:01:27.669 --> 00:01:29.836
this applies to both of these columns.

00:01:29.836 --> 00:01:31.840
This is for what it was $1 per bar,

00:01:31.840 --> 00:01:33.999
this is now when it's $2 per bar.

00:01:33.999 --> 00:01:37.836
Well, for that first bar,
I'm still getting 100 points

00:01:37.836 --> 00:01:40.832
of marginal utility, but now it's $2.

00:01:40.832 --> 00:01:44.474
So 100 divided 2 is going to give me

00:01:44.474 --> 00:01:48.331
50 marginal utility points per dollar.

00:01:48.331 --> 00:01:51.075
Then for that next bar,

00:01:51.075 --> 00:01:53.733
I get 80 marginal utility points.

00:01:53.733 --> 00:01:56.283
I'm still enjoying it but
enjoying it a little bit less

00:01:56.283 --> 00:01:58.124
but I'm paying $2 for it.

00:01:58.124 --> 00:02:01.334
I'm getting 80 divided by 2 is 40 points,

00:02:01.334 --> 00:02:03.472
you know, and I'm just
giving these arbitrary units,

00:02:03.472 --> 00:02:05.538
40 points per dollar.

00:02:05.538 --> 00:02:08.008
Then the 3rd bar is 30 points per dollar.

00:02:08.008 --> 00:02:12.537
Then the 4th bar is 20 points per dollar.

00:02:12.537 --> 00:02:16.267
Now, how would I spend my $5?

00:02:16.267 --> 00:02:17.703
Let me do this a little bit,

00:02:17.703 --> 00:02:18.933
let me do it over here.

00:02:18.933 --> 00:02:21.876
How would I spend my $5 now?

